l that does exactly this for<br>\nGNU/Linux in general or on Debian in particular. \xa0If you find one I<br>\nwould be interested in it.<br>\n<br>\nThere are some useful tools available though. \xa0You might look at &#39;ibam&#39;.<br>\n<br>\n \xa0IBAM is an advanced battery monitor for laptops, which uses<br>\n \xa0statistical and adaptive linear methods to provide accurate<br>\n \xa0estimations of minutes of battery left or of the time needed until<br>\n \xa0full recharge. It requires APM, ACPI or PMU.<br>\n<br>\nIt needs some training. \xa0But given that it does perform fairly well.<br>\nUnfortunately it isn&#39;t tied into the system tray tools and so isn&#39;t<br>\ngoing to be a seemless integration there. \xa0It is available in gkrellm<br>\nif you use that stack. \xa0See the gkrellm-ibam package.<br>\n<font color="#888888"><br>\nBob<br>\n</font><br>-----BEGIN PGP SIGNATURE-----<br>\nVersion: GnuPG v1.4.9 (GNU/Linux)<br>\n<br>\niEYEARECAAYFAkvMyzoACgkQ0pRcO8E2ULYdhACdGU6+dGFyC/JEBZ7ZKJ1DADeQ<br>\nQQIAnifmqo0x0oW6l6rSl4pqZdpuTG6z<br>\n=EbsH<br>\n-----END PGP SIGNATURE-----<br>\n<br></blockquote></div><br><br clear="all"><br>-- <br>Mit freundlichen Grüßen<br><br>Zichen Chen<br>\n', 'subject': 'Re: Battery monitor tools?'}